    <stitle>CAB: 2000, 4000, AND 8000 - ADJUSTMENTS - STAY RODS</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc id="x1600710" svcproctype="IDcomponent" graphiccount="1">
        <title>STAY RODS</title>
        <para>Periodic adjustment of the stay rods may be necessary. Inspection of the stay rod will reveal if
            adjustment is necessary. Anytime the stay rods have been removed and replaced or the adjusting nuts have
            been tampered with, the stay rods have to be re-adjusted.
        </para>
        <para>Refer to
            <hotlnk xrefid="f1600757">Figure 57</hotlnk>for Items in parentheses.
        </para>
        <figure id="f1600757" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1600757" filename="../figg16/g1600757.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 57. Stay Rod</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. NUT</callout1>
                <callout1>2. STAY ROD INSULATOR</callout1>
                <callout1>3. STAY ROD</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Loosen the four nuts (Item 1), two on each end, of the stay rod (Item 3) to relieve total
                compression of the insulators (Item 2) on both sides of the mounting bracket.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Adjust the outer nut (Item 1) on one end of the stay rod until the insulators (Item 2) are
                equally compressed. Tighten to 19 to 27 ft-lbs. (26 to 37 N&#183;m).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Adjust the nuts (Item 1) on the opposite end of the stay rod in the same manner as in Step
                2.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Repeat this procedure on the opposite stay rod.</para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
